          "response": "1. **Assumption: Messy inputs contain enough information to support a correct conclusion.**  \n   **Why It\u2019s Hidden:** Nearly every concept begins with \u201cpaste,\u201d \u201cupload,\u201d or \u201csnap,\u201d making transformation appear to be the hard part. The ideas quietly assume the input includes the real constraints, decisions, causal history, or learning gaps.  \n   **What If It\u2019s Wrong:** The product must ask follow-up questions or access additional sources. \u201cOne Question Left,\u201d \u201cMeeting Autopsy,\u201d \u201cBug Storyboard Builder,\u201d and \u201cVibeCheck\u201d could confidently invent consensus, causality, or constraints\u2014destroying their central promise of instant resolution.\n\n2. **Assumption: AI can reliably distinguish subtle reasoning from plausible-looking language.**  \n   **Why It\u2019s Hidden:** Structured diagrams, scores, highlights, and receipts make probabilistic judgments feel objective.  \n   **What If It\u2019s Wrong:** The strongest diagnostic ideas become actively misleading. \u201cFirst Wrong Turn\u201d may flag a valid algebra step; \u201cClaim Evidence Receipt\u201d may confuse topical similarity with support; \u201cFine Print Flags\u201d may overstate legal risk; \u201cFeynman Live\u201d may reward fluent but incorrect explanations. These products would need narrow domains, deterministic validation, citations, or human review.\n\n3. **Assumption: Users can and will provide sensitive source material.**  \n   **Why It\u2019s Hidden:** Brainstorming treats transcripts, repositories, care notes, emails, leases, and workplace files as frictionless demo inputs rather than governed data.  \n   **What If It\u2019s Wrong:** Privacy, consent, permissions, and organizational policy become the actual product problem. \u201cCare Relay Card,\u201d \u201cDigestify,\u201d \u201cContextSwitch,\u201d and group-chat tools may lose access to their essential inputs or require integrations and security work far beyond a three-day build.\n\n4. **Assumption: A compelling one-shot demo predicts sustained user value.**  \n   **Why It\u2019s Hidden:** The ideas are optimized for judge-visible \u201caha\u201d moments: chaos enters, clarity appears. That rewards immediate legibility more than repeated use or measurable behavior change.  \n   **What If It\u2019s Wrong:** Concepts such as \u201cComplexity Dial,\u201d \u201cFuture Self Receipt,\u201d and \u201cFive Second Mirror\u201d may win attention but lack retention. The better product may be less theatrical and more deeply embedded in an existing workflow.\n\n5. **Assumption: Users will trust AI to collapse ambiguity into one answer.**  \n   **Why It\u2019s Hidden:** Decisiveness is framed as relief from cognitive load.  \n   **What If It\u2019s Wrong:** \u201cOne Question Left\u201d\u2014arguably the most promising idea\u2014loses its advantage. Users may dispute omitted preferences or resist algorithmic compromise, requiring visible evidence, uncertainty, corrections, and appeal mechanisms."
