u201d \u201cfirst wrong,\u201d \u201cunsupported,\u201d or \u201cWCAG-grade\u201d outputs require objective evaluation criteria. Without them, neither builders nor users can verify quality.\n\n**4. Connections**\n\nThese assumptions form a dependency chain: accessible input \u2192 sufficient evidence \u2192 reliable inference \u2192 trusted output \u2192 user action \u2192 repeat value. If Analyst A\u2019s \u201cclean raw input\u201d assumption fails, accuracy claims cannot even be evaluated. If Analyst B\u2019s reliability assumption fails, decisive interfaces amplify rather than contain the error. If trust then fails, even accurate future outputs will not change behavior. Consequently, One Question Left and First Wrong Turn are promising only if they expose evidence, uncertainty, and correction\u2014not merely polished conclusions."
