dd, or delete nodes on the canvas. This design turns an LLM reasoning error into an active, collaborative feature (\"As you can see, I can easily correct this missing path manually\"). Static text-generation tools like *Complexity Dial* or the original *OQL* do not have this safety net; if they fail, the user is left helpless.\n\n---\n\n### Top 5 Innovation Ideas Evaluation\n\n| Dimension | Score | Justification |\n|-----------|-------|---------------|\n| **1. State Gap Mapper** (Codex #3) | | **Total: 44/50** |\n| Market Need | 8/10 | Catching edge cases in product specifications saves massive engineering overhead. |\n| Differentiation | 9/10 | Moves beyond simple code generation into visual systems engineering and logical verification. |\n| Feasibility | 9/10 | Text-to-Graph using standard Mermaid.js or React Flow is highly deterministic and robust. |\n| Risk | 9/10 | High. The interactive, editable canvas acts as an insurance policy against LLM diagramming errors. |\n| Impact | 9/10 | Provides deep utility for product managers, QA engineers, and developers alike. |\n| **2. Complexity Dial** (Kimi #1) | | **Total: 42/50** |\n| Market Need | 9/10 | Solves critical accessibility barriers in healthcare, legal, and academic texts. |\n| Differentiation | 8/10 | Outstanding \"single-gesture\" slider UI turns a basic summary tool into an interactive toy. |\n| Feasibility | 9/10 | Highly feasible; relies entirely on prompt-engineered text-to-text generation. |\n| Risk | 8/10 | Moderate; prone to oversimplification errors at lower reading levels (e.g., \"Age 5\"). |\n| Impact | 8/10 | Broad, universal application, but lacks a persistent multi-user engagement hook. |\n| **3. One Question Left (Re-framed)** (Codex #1) | | **Total: 40/50** |\n| Market Need | 8/10 | Resolves group coordination paralysis, a highly relatable consumer pain point. |\n| Differentiation | 8/10 | Frames AI as a discussion *closer* rather than a generator of more text. |\n| Feasibility | 8/10 | Feasible if we pivot from a \"single question\" to a ranked \"top three unresolved forks.\" |\n| Risk | 7/10 | Moderate; re-framing the output into a choice list reduces the risk of a single wrong deduction. |\n| Impact | 9/10 | High viral potential due to shareable voting cards and lightweight web-app structure. |\n| **4. TailwindTuner** (Gemini #5) | | **Total: 39/50** |\n| Market Need | 8/10 | Greatly accelerates front-end design-to-development cycles. |\n| Differentiation | 7/10 | Highly saturated space; must compete conceptually with established giants like v0.dev. |\n| Feasibility | 8/10 | Component generation is well-supported, but real-time canvas-to-code sync is complex. |\n| Risk | 8/10 | Low risk of total failure, but UI lag could ruin the \"magic\" of the live demo. |\n| Impact | 8/10 | High productivity boost for developers, though limited to Tailwind/React ecosystems. |\n| **5. Claim Evidence Receipt** (Codex #6) | | **Total: 38/50** |\n| Market Need | 8/10 | Crucial for checking hallucination in AI outputs and verifying professional reports. |\n| Differentiation | 7/10 | Provenance checking is powerful, but visually less \"flashy\" for a quick hackathon pitch. |\n| Feasibility | 8/10 | Highly feasible; uses citation-alignment mapping between source and draft. |\n| Risk | 7/10 | Moderate; attribution mapping can fail to capture nuanced, paraphrased claims. |\n| Impact | 8/10 | Delivers high trust and security for professional knowledge workers. |\n\n---\n\n### Top 3 Recommendations\n\n1. **State Gap Mapper (Codex #3):** The premier choice. It delivers a stunning, technical visual output (React Flow state graphs) that is fully interactive, shielding the presenter from LLM generation errors while providing massive value to product and engineering teams.\n2. **Complexity Dial (Kimi #1):** The ultimate \"crowd-pleaser\" demo. It provides an immediate, highly intuitive user experience that anyone on the judging panel can instantly understand and play with.\n3. **