ic papers) and see them translate live.\n3. **One Question Left [Re-framed] (Codex #1):** The viral consumer wild card. By pivoting from a fragile single-question guess to an editable list of top unresolved forks, it delivers high engagement with minimized live-demo risk.\n\n---\n\n### Final Debate Position\n\n#### 1. Final Position\nWe must build **State Gap Mapper**. It is the ultimate hackathon submission, pairing highly legible, instant visual output (React Flow state graphs) with a robust, interactive canvas that protects against LLM reasoning errors.\n\n#### 2. Key Reasoning\n*   **The Editable Canvas Insurance Policy:** The biggest threat to an AI hackathon demo is a silent LLM hallucination. *State Gap Mapper* neutralizes this. If the model generates an imperfect state machine from a user's requirements, the user can visually drag-and-drop, edit, or delete nodes live on the canvas. This design turns a potential AI failure into a collaborative, impressive product feature.\n*   **Substantive Technical Depth:** Unlike simple text-in/text-out wrappers, *State Gap Mapper* showcases complex system engineering\u2014converting requirements into schema-constrained JSON, rendering interactive graphs, running gap-analysis algorithms, and generating automated test cases. It directly targets the highest-weight technical implementation rubrics.\n\n#### 3. Concessions\nI concede to Positions B and C that the original *One Question Left* carries an unacceptably high risk of demo-killing failure; misidentifying the single \"decisive question\" destroys the entire value proposition instantly. I also agree with Position C that *Complexity Dial* requires a source-linked verification toggle to prevent semantic degradation and hallucination at extreme simplification levels.\n\n#### 4. Remaining Disagreements\nI strongly disagree with Position C's ranking of *Complexity Dial* as the #1 choice. While it is highly polished and has a low barrier to entry, it is conceptually \"one pro