      "response": "**1. Strongest assumption**\n\nAnalyst C\u2019s \u201cdemo legibility is a proxy for product value\u201d is the strongest\u2014but specifically within a hackathon. Judges have limited time, so products with an immediate, visible state change are easier to understand and reward. Complexity Dial, First Wrong Turn, and One Question Left all communicate their value in seconds. This does not prove retention, as Analyst B noted, but it is a credible proxy for judging performance.\n\n**2. Weakest assumption**\n\nAnalyst A\u2019s \u201cdesire for cognitive friction\u201d is least likely to hold broadly. Evidence from educational products suggests active recall and deliberate practice can improve learning, but effectiveness does not imply voluntary adoption. Users frequently choose answer engines over tutoring loops, especially when rushed. Socratic, Feynman Live, and Negotiation Dojo therefore assume not only that effort helps, but that users will repeatedly choose it. That is a much weaker behavioral claim.\n\nAnalyst C\u2019s point that coordination paralysis is social rather than informational is also important, but too absolute. Some coordination failures genuinely are missing-constraint problems; others involve status, politeness, or low commitment. The coordination ideas are not invalidated universally\u2014they need to distinguish computational ambiguity from social resistance.\n\n**3. Missing assumptions**\n\nEveryone underweights four assumptions:\n\n- **Correction is cheap:** Users can notice and repair an incorrect extraction. Often they cannot identify what the model omitted.\n- **The output changes behavior:** A clear recommendation, warning, or receipt is assumed to produce action rather than momentary interest.\n- **Standalone differentiation exists:** Incumbents such as ChatGPT, IDE copilots, email suites, and document platforms may reproduce the core feature quickly.\n- **Ground truth is available:** Products promising \u201coptimal,\u201d \u201cfirst wrong,\u201d \u201cunsupported,\u201d or \u201cWCAG-grade\u201d outputs require objective evaluation criteria. Without them, neither builders nor users can verify quality.\n\n**4. Connections**\n\nThese assumptions form a dependency chain: accessible input \u2192 sufficient evidence \u2192 reliable inference \u2192 trusted output \u2192 user action \u2192 repeat value. If Analyst A\u2019s \u201cclean raw input\u201d assumption fails, accuracy claims cannot even be evaluated. If Analyst B\u2019s reliability assumption fails, decisive interfaces amplify rather than contain the error. If trust then fails, even accurate future outputs will not change behavior. Consequently, One Question Left and First Wrong Turn are promising only if they expose evidence, uncertainty, and correction\u2014not merely polished conclusions.",
