      "response": "# Analyst C \u2014 Cross-Examination\n\n## 1. Strongest Assumption: Analyst A's \"Clean Raw Input\" \u2014 for text only\nMost likely to hold. LLMs demonstrably parse disfluent, fragmented transcripts, and real group chats genuinely contain stated constraints (\"can't do Tuesdays\"). But I'd split it from Analyst B's stronger version (#1): signal *legibility* is robust; signal *completeness* is not. Logs notoriously omit the causal event \u2014 *Bug Storyboard Builder* breaks where *VibeCheck* survives. The assumption is strong for chat text, weak for telemetry and photos.\n\n## 2. Weakest Assumption: Analyst A's \"Desire for Cognitive Friction\"\nThe empirical record is brutal: Photomath won by giving answers; Google's actual app named *Socratic* is an answer engine, not an RPG; Duolingo burns enormous effort fighting abandonment of exactly these effortful loops. This single assumption props up *Socratic*, *First Wrong Turn*, *Negotiation Dojo*, *Feynman Live*, and arguably *Future Self Receipt*. Worse, it's the one assumption model progress won't fix \u2014 you can't engineer around human preference for shortcuts. (My own #4 \u2014 meaning preserved at \"age 5\" for medical text \u2014 is a close second.)\n\n## 3. Missing Assumptions\n- **The wrapper assumption.** Everyone assumed users open a dedicated tool rather than paste the same content into the ChatGPT tab already open. Single-transaction paste tools carry no retained state or switching costs; only ideas with persistent artifacts (*SchemaScribe*'s live endpoint, *TailwindTuner*'s synced canvas) survive absorption.\n- **The consequence-symmetry assumption.** Analysts debated accuracy, not *cost of error*. *Fine Print Flags*' \"walk-away score,\" *Care Relay*'s medication extraction, and *Complexity Dial*'s age-5 discharge summary all assume mistakes are free. In legal/medical/care domains, one miss is catastrophic and liability-bearing \u2014 a bar no 3-day build clears.\n- **The deputization assumption.** Group tools assume the paste-er has authority. Five friends never consented to abide by a verdict extracted from their own words.\n\n## 4. Connections: A Serial Funnel\nThe assumptions form a dependency chain: **Access** (A#3/C#1) \u2192 **Signal** (A#1/B#1) \u2192 **Accuracy** (B#2/C#2) \u2192 **Social acceptance** (C#3/B#5) \u2192 **Retention** (B#4/C#5). Each gates the next; truth downstream cannot rescue failure upstream. Critically, the gates split into *model-fixable* (signal, accuracy \u2014 strengthen every model generation) and *human-fixed* (friction-aversion, buy-in, consent). My #3 being wrong doesn't invalidate A#1 \u2014 it *moots* it: a perfectly parsed chat whose verdict the group ignores is worthless. And B#2 cascades into B#5: inaccuracy is the leading cause of distrust. Meta-level: hackathon judging (my #5) selects for demo legibility, which correlates precisely with ideas dying at the human-fixed gates \u2014 the process optimizes for the wrong survival criteria.",
